<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-019-131 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 475 869</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Shopper  Nov 1991 v11 n11 p831(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>LAPGUARD offers corporate data security for portable PCs.andO;(Personal Computer Card Corp.'s data security software) (NewProduct Watch) (Product Announcement)andM;</TITLE><SUMMARY>Personal Computer Card Corp introduces its $99 LAPGUARD datasecurity software package that ensures security for portablemicrocomputers.andP;  The system comprises security software and aspecial card that inserts into a computer's 3.5-inch floppy diskdrive.andP;  The special card functions as a disk that cannot becopied.andP;  In addition to the disk security element, a specialpassword is also required of the user before accessing files.andP;  Theuser first inserts the special card, then inputs a personalidentification number.andP;  Users can program the cards to permitaccess to any number of files.andP;  A utility is included thatdemonstrates how to encrypt and hide files on a hard or floppydisk.andP;  Encryption can make files invisible to any directory searchor listing.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Personal Computer Card Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   LapGuard (Data security software) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionData SecuritySecurity SoftwarePortable Computers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Keeping your data under lock and key is one way to keep snoopers away.andM;But that's only good for desktop systems.andP;  Portable PCs remain the weak linkin a company's defense scheme.andM;And as laptop PCs proliferate--sometimes replacing desktop computers--in thecorporate world, the need for sure-fire data security systems has growncommensurately.andM;The Personal Computer Card Corporation, also known as PC3, has developedLAPGUARD, a password-based laptop security system that requires both apersonal identification number and a disk functioning as a key, KEYDISK,which cannot be copied or counterfeited and fits into a standard 3.5-inchdrive.andM;PC3 derived LAPGUARD from its existing &quot;Smart Card&quot; desktop security system.andO;Smart Card is somewhat like an automated bank teller.andM;The user must first insert a plastic access card into an externally mountedreader and then enter a PIN.andM;Unlike a bank card, however, the Smart Card contains a &quot;micro-module,&quot; bothmicrocomputer and memory, embedded in its surface.andM;Cards can be programmed to permit access to one, several, or all presentfiles.andM;The designers took their jobs seriously, but not without a sense of humor.andM;The product includes a utility that allows users to encrypt and hide files ona hard disk or floppy, making them invisible to any directory listing orsearch.andM;When unauthorized access is attempted, however, LAPGUARD &quot;barks&quot; at theintruder, notifying every one in the area that you are violating the &quot;NOPETS&quot; rule in the hotel.andP;  Fur and wet nose are not included.andM;LAPGUARD lists for $99.andP;  Contact Personal Computer Card Corp., 5015 S.andO;Florida Ave., Suite 102, Lakeland, FL 33813; 1-800-922-1079.andO;</TEXT></DOC>